#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:10
msgid "1.1 The Spin-Glass Analogy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:12
msgid ""
"The conceptual bridge between statistical physics and neural networks "
"rests on a powerful analogy: neurons can be treated as tiny magnets, and "
"their collective behavior can be described using the language of "
"statistical mechanics. This connection, first fully exploited by John "
"Hopfield in 1982, provides the foundational framework for understanding "
"the Boltzmann Machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:14
msgid "<b>The Ising Model of Magnetism</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:16
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"In condensed matter physics, the Ising model describes a system of "
"interacting magnetic spins. Each spin $s_i$ resides on a lattice site and"
" can point either \"up\" $(s_i = +1 )$ or \"down\" $( s_i = -1)$. The "
"energy of a particular spin configuration $\\mathbf{s} = (s_1, s_2, "
"\\ldots, s_N)$is given by the Hamiltonian:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:18
#, python-brace-format
msgid "E(\\mathbf{s}) = -\\sum_{i<j} J_{ij} s_i s_j - \\sum_i h_i s_i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:20
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Here, $J_{ij}$ represents the interaction strength (coupling) between "
"spins $i$and $j$. If $J_{ij} > 0$, the interaction is "
"<b>ferromagnetic</b>: the spins prefer to align in the same direction to "
"lower the energy. If $J_{ij} < 0$, the interaction is "
"<b>antiferromagnetic</b>: the spins prefer opposite alignment. The term "
"$h_i$ represents an external magnetic field biasing individual spins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:22
msgid ""
"At thermal equilibrium with a heat bath at temperature $T$, the "
"probability of observing a given spin configuration follows the "
"<b>Boltzmann distribution</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:24
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{s}) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{E(\\mathbf{s})}{k_B "
"T}\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:26
msgid ""
"where $k_B$ is Boltzmann's constant and $Z = \\sum_{\\mathbf{s}} "
"\\exp(-E(\\mathbf{s})/k_B T)$ is the partition function. At low "
"temperatures, the system freezes into low-energy, ordered states. At high"
" temperatures, thermal fluctuations dominate and spins become randomly "
"oriented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:28
msgid "<b>Neurons as Spins, Synapses as Couplings</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:30
msgid ""
"The transition from magnetic spins to neural networks requires only a "
"change of interpretation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:48
msgid ""
"With this dictionary, the energy function of a recurrent neural network "
"becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:50
#, python-brace-format
msgid "E(\\mathbf{x}) = -\\sum_{i<j} w_{ij} x_i x_j - \\sum_i b_i x_i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:52
msgid "or, in matrix form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:54
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E_\\theta(\\mathbf{x}) = -\\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{x} - "
"\\frac{1}{2}\\mathbf{x}^\\top \\mathbf{W} \\mathbf{x}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:56
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $\\mathbf{W}$ is a symmetric weight matrix with zero diagonal "
"$(w_{ii} = 0)$. The symmetry requirement $w_{ij} = w_{ji}$ is crucial "
"because it ensures that the system possesses a well-defined energy "
"landscape and will eventually settle into an equilibrium distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:58
msgid "<b>Why Quadratic Energy?  </b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:60
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The energy function $E = -\\sum w_{ij}x_i x_j$ is the simplest possible "
"form for a system with pairwise interactions. It represents the sum of "
"interactions between every pair of units. This is the same form as the "
"Ising Hamiltonian. More complex (higher-order) interactions are possible "
"but are much harder to work with. This quadratic form is the 'first-"
"order' approximation of a many-body system, making it the natural "
"starting point for both physics and neural network models."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:62
msgid "<b>Statistical Physics Foundations: The Microcanonical Ensemble</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:64
msgid ""
"To understand the probabilistic behavior of such a system, we must invoke"
" the <b>fundamental assumption of statistical physics</b>: For an "
"isolated system at equilibrium, all accessible microstates "
"(configurations) consistent with the system's macroscopic constraints "
"(e.g., total energy) are equally probable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:66
msgid ""
"This principle gives rise to the <b>microcanonical ensemble</b>. For a "
"system with fixed energy $E$, volume $V$, and number of particles $N$, "
"the number of microstates with energy in the range $(E, E + \\delta E)$ "
"is denoted $\\Omega(E, V, N)$. The <b>Boltzmann entropy</b> is then "
"defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:68
msgid "S(E, V, N) = k \\log \\Omega(E, V, N)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:70
msgid ""
"where $k$ is Boltzmann's constant. This entropy measures the number of "
"microscopic configurations consistent with a given macrostate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:72
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"For a macroscopic system (e.g., $N \\sim 10^{23}$), $\\Omega$ is an "
"astronomically large number, and the entropy is extensive, i.e. it scales"
" linearly with $N$. This is why the second law of thermodynamics holds: "
"the system evolves toward the macrostate with the largest number of "
"microstates (highest entropy)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:74
msgid "<b>Spin Glasses and Frustration</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:76
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"A <b>spin glass</b> is a magnetic system in which the coupling strengths "
"$J_{ij}$ are random and contain both positive (ferromagnetic) and "
"negative (antiferromagnetic) values. This mixture creates "
"<b>frustration</b>: a single spin cannot simultaneously satisfy the "
"competing demands of all its neighbors. As a result, the energy landscape"
" of a spin glass is rugged, containing a vast number of <b>metastable "
"states</b> (local minima) separated by energy barriers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:78
msgid ""
"This is precisely the scenario we encounter in neural networks designed "
"for associative memory. When we store multiple patterns using a Hebbian "
"learning rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:80
#, python-brace-format
msgid "w_{ij} = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{\\mu=1}^P \\xi_i^\\mu \\xi_j^\\mu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:82
msgid ""
"we are effectively engineering a spin glass whose low-energy "
"configurations correspond to the stored memories $ "
"\\{\\boldsymbol{\\xi}^\\mu\\}$. However, because the weight matrix mixes "
"contributions from different memories, the energy landscape inevitably "
"develops <b>spurious minima</b>—states that are not stored patterns but "
"nevertheless trap the network dynamics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:84
msgid "<b>From Deterministic Dynamics to Stochastic Search</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:86
msgid "Hopfield's original network employed deterministic, asynchronous updates:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:88
#, python-brace-format
msgid "x_i \\leftarrow \\text{sign}\\left( \\sum_{j} w_{ij} x_j + b_i \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:90
msgid ""
"This dynamics is equivalent to moving strictly downhill in the energy "
"landscape. The network will converge to the nearest local minimum, but it"
" may get stuck in a spurious state rather than the intended memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:92
msgid ""
"The <b>Boltzmann Machine</b> introduces a crucial modification: updates "
"become <b>stochastic</b>. At a finite temperature $T$, a neuron $i$ is "
"set to state $1$ with probability:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:94
msgid "P(x_i = 1) = \\sigma\\left( \\frac{\\sum_j w_{ij} x_j + b_i}{T} \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-spinglass.md:96
msgid ""
"where $ \\sigma(z) = 1/(1 + \\exp(-z))$ is the sigmoid function. Thermal "
"noise occasionally pushes the system <em>uphill</em>, allowing it to "
"escape shallow local minima and explore the energy landscape more "
"thoroughly. As the temperature is gradually reduced (<b>simulated "
"annealing</b>), the system is more likely to settle into a deep, low-"
"energy state corresponding to a true memory."
msgstr ""

